### Frontend Design System

This file documents the **actual design conventions in the codebase**, not
aspirations. The two structural rules ("no inline CSS/JS in templates",
"shared assets under `front/static/`") live in
`05-code-style-and-structure.mdc § Frontend (HTML/CSS/JS)`. This file
covers visual language, components, naming and asset wiring.

### Design Token Systems (two coexisting scopes)

There are **two namespaced token systems**, by design — do not mix them.

| Scope | File | Prefix | Theme |
|-------|------|--------|-------|
| App shell (navbar, pages, modals, forms, KPI tiles, etc.) | `src/front/static/global/css/main.css` | `--db-*` | Databricks Red on light grey |
| OntoViz canvas (entity boxes, relationships, toolbar) | `src/front/static/global/ontoviz/css/ontoviz-variables.css` | `--ovz-*` | Greyscale only |

**Rules:**

- Always use a token. Never hard-code a colour, shadow, radius or transition
  that has a token equivalent.
- Inside `static/global/ontoviz/**`, use `--ovz-*` tokens only.
- Everywhere else under `static/**` and `templates/**`, use `--db-*` tokens.
- Do not introduce a third namespace. If a new token is needed, extend the
  appropriate file (`main.css :root` or `ontoviz-variables.css :root`).

### Colour Palette (`--db-*`)

| Role | Token | Value |
|------|-------|-------|
| Brand primary | `--db-primary` | `#FF3621` (Databricks Red) |
| Primary dark / darker | `--db-primary-dark`, `--db-primary-darker` | `#E62E1C`, `#CC2819` |
| Primary tint (focus rings, badges) | `--db-primary-light` | `rgba(255, 54, 33, 0.1)` |
| Surface dark (navbar) | `--db-dark`, `--db-gray` | `#1B1C1D`, `#2C2D2E` |
| Page background | `--db-light-gray` | `#F7F7F7` |
| Borders | `--db-border`, `--db-border-light` | `#E0E0E0`, `#dee2e6` |
| Text | `--db-text`, `--db-text-secondary`, `--db-text-muted` | `#1E1E1E`, `#6B6C6D`, `#666666` |
| Status | `--db-success`, `--db-warning`, `--db-info`, `--db-success-bg`, `--db-success-text`, `--db-danger-bg`, `--db-danger-text` | Bootstrap-aligned |
| Shadows | `--db-shadow-sm`, `--db-shadow-md`, `--db-shadow-lg`, `--db-shadow-primary` | layered |
| Transitions | `--db-transition`, `--db-transition-fast` | `0.2s` / `0.15s ease` |

### Where Primary Red Is (and Is Not) Allowed

Primary red (`--db-primary`) is **reserved** for high-signal moments:

- Navbar brand, navbar active state, navbar dropdown hover/active.
- Workflow step circles and the connecting line on the home page.
- Form-control focus ring (`box-shadow: 0 0 0 0.2rem rgba(var(--db-primary-rgb), 0.25)`).
- `.badge-primary`, `.bg-primary`, `.text-primary`, `.border-primary` utility overrides.
- The OntoBricks loading spinner accent.

**Primary red is NOT allowed on plain buttons.** All Bootstrap colored button
variants (`.btn-primary`, `.btn-success`, `.btn-danger`, …, including
`.btn-outline-*`) are deliberately **forced to a neutral grey palette** in
`global/css/components.css`. When a contributor reaches for `class="btn
btn-success"`, they get the same grey button as `btn-secondary` — this is
intentional. Convey state via icon, label, or a sibling `.badge` /
`.alert`, not via button colour.

### Typography

- System font stack only:
  `-apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, "Segoe UI", Roboto, "Helvetica Neue", Arial, sans-serif`.
- No webfont imports. No `@font-face`. No Google Fonts.
- OntoViz uses `--ovz-font-main`, `--ovz-font-display`, `--ovz-font-mono`
  defined in `ontoviz-variables.css`.
- Page header sizes: `.page-header h1` = `2rem` / `600` weight; subtitle
  paragraph = secondary text colour.

### Iconography

- **Bootstrap Icons** only (`<i class="bi bi-..."></i>`), loaded from CDN in
  `base.html`.
- Menu/sidebar icons are configured **declaratively** in
  `src/front/config/menu_config.json` (`"icon": "bi-..."`), never hard-coded
  in templates.
- Do not introduce another icon font, SVG icon library, or emoji-as-icon.

### Page Layout (mandatory skeleton)

Every page **must** extend `templates/base.html`. The base template owns
the entire app chrome — never duplicate or substitute any of it:

| Element | Provided by `base.html` | Don't reimplement |
|---------|-------------------------|-------------------|
| Navbar (top) | `<nav class="navbar navbar-expand-lg navbar-dark">` driven by `menu_config.json` | a custom top bar |
| Breadcrumb | `#obBreadcrumb` / `.ob-breadcrumb`, populated by `breadcrumb.js` | a per-page breadcrumb |
| Domain loading overlay | `#domainLoadingOverlay` / `.domain-loading-overlay` | another full-page spinner |
| Notification Center dropdown | `#notifCenterDropdown` (bell) | a per-page notif list |
| Task Tracker dropdown | `#taskTrackerDropdown` (hourglass) | a per-page task panel |
| Help Center modal | included via `partials/layout/help_modal.html` | a custom help dialog |
| UC File Browser modal | included via `partials/layout/uc_file_browser_modal.html` | another file picker |
| Body data attributes | `data-app-role`, `data-domain-role`, `data-app-mode` | re-fetching them |
| Bootstrap JS bundle | loaded after `{% block content %}` | re-loading Bootstrap |

A page template **must** look like this (and nothing more at the top
level):

```html
{% extends "base.html" %}

{% block title %}<Page Name> - OntoBricks{% endblock %}

{% block extra_css %}
<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='<area>/css/<area>-<feature>.css') }}?v={{ asset_version }}">
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
   ...one of the two layout patterns below...
{% endblock %}

{% block extra_js %}
<script src="{{ url_for('static', filename='<area>/js/<area>-<feature>.js') }}?v={{ asset_version }}"></script>
{% endblock %}
```

There are exactly **two** acceptable layouts inside `{% block content %}`.
Pick one, do not invent a third.

#### Layout 1 — Sidebar layout (default for app pages)

Used by `ontology.html`, `mapping.html`, `dtwin.html`, `registry.html`,
`domain.html`, `settings.html`. This is the default for any page that
exposes more than one functional section.

```html
<div class="container-fluid px-0">
    <div class="sidebar-layout">
        <!-- Left sidebar - rendered from menu_config.json -->
        <div class="sidebar-nav">
            {% set sidebar_menu = get_menu('<area>') %}
            {% include "partials/layout/_sidebar_nav.html" %}
        </div>

        <!-- Right content area: one section per sidebar item -->
        <div class="sidebar-content">
            <div id="information-section" class="sidebar-section active">
                {% include "partials/<area>/_<area>_information.html" %}
            </div>
            <div id="design-section" class="sidebar-section">
                {% include "partials/<area>/_<area>_design.html" %}
            </div>
            <!-- ...one <div id="<id>-section" class="sidebar-section"> per menu item... -->
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
```

Rules for sidebar pages:

- The sidebar **must** be the `_sidebar_nav.html` partial driven by
  `menu_config.json` — never hand-code `<nav class="sidebar-nav">` items.
- Section ids are `<menu-item-id>-section`. The id must match the
  `data-section` attribute emitted by the partial for the
  section-switcher to pick it up (`sidebar-nav.js`).
- Exactly **one** section carries `.active` on initial render (typically
  the menu item flagged `default: true`, or the section name passed via
  `?section=...` querystring).
- Each section's body lives in a partial under
  `templates/partials/<area>/_<area>_<feature>.html`. Page templates
  never inline the section bodies.
- `.content-wrapper` constraints are intentionally overridden when a
  `.sidebar-layout` is present (see `sidebar-layout.css`) — full width,
  full viewport height minus chrome. Do not re-add `padding` or
  `max-width` on the wrapper.

#### Layout 2 — Standalone content (single-purpose pages only)

Used by `home.html`, `about.html`, `access_denied.html`. Reserve for
landing/info pages that do not need a sidebar.

```html
{# Content sits inside base.html's default .content-wrapper:
   max-width: 1400px, padding: 2rem, auto-centred #}
<div class="page-header">
    <h1><i class="bi bi-..."></i> Page Title</h1>
    <p>Optional subtitle in --db-text-secondary.</p>
</div>

<!-- ...page content... -->
```

Rules for standalone pages:

- Use `.page-header` for the title block — do not invent another header
  treatment.
- Stay inside the default `.content-wrapper`. Do not wrap the content in
  `.container-fluid` or override the wrapper's max-width.

### Sidebar Behaviour

The sidebar is a self-contained component owned by
`global/js/sidebar-nav.js` + `global/css/sidebar-layout.css`. Page code
**must not** reimplement section switching, collapse, URL sync or
keyboard handling.

**Auto-init contract**

- `sidebar-nav.js` auto-initialises on `DOMContentLoaded` whenever a
  `.sidebar-nav` exists. To opt out (extremely rare), set
  `window.SIDEBAR_NAV_MANUAL_INIT = true` *before* the script runs and
  call `SidebarNav.init({...})` yourself.
- Each nav item must carry `data-section="<id>"` and the corresponding
  content block must have id `"<id>-section"` and class
  `"sidebar-section"`. Mismatch = silent no-op.
- Exactly one `.nav-link` and one `.sidebar-section` carry `.active` at
  any time. Never set `display: none / block` directly on a section —
  the `.active` class is what the CSS reads.

**State, history and keyboard**

- The active section is mirrored to `?section=<id>` in the URL via
  `history.pushState`, and restored from query string or hash on load
  and on `popstate` (Back / Forward work).
- Collapsed/expanded state is persisted in `localStorage` under
  `ontobricks-sidebar-collapsed`. **Default state is collapsed** — do
  not change this default.
- The collapse toggle button is injected automatically at the top of
  the sidebar. Do not author your own toggle.
- A `sidebarSectionChanged` `CustomEvent` (`detail: { section,
  targetSection }`) is dispatched on `document` after every switch.
  This is the official extension point — listen to it instead of
  patching click handlers.

**Public API (use these, not raw DOM manipulation)**

| Call | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `SidebarNav.switchTo(name)` | Programmatically activate a section |
| `SidebarNav.getActiveSection()` | Read the current section id |
| `SidebarNav.toggleCollapse()` | Programmatically collapse/expand |
| `SidebarNav.init({ onSectionChange, onBeforeSectionChange })` | Re-init with hooks; `onBeforeSectionChange` may return `false` (or a Promise resolving to `false`) to veto the switch |

**Style rules**

- Sidebar width: `200px` expanded, `48px` collapsed (driven by
  `.sidebar-nav.collapsed`). Do not override per page.
- Nav-link visual: `0.82rem`, left-border accent of `3px transparent`
  that grows on `:hover` and `.active`. Active background is
  `rgba(0,0,0,0.15)` (greyscale by design — do not colourise).
- Section group titles (`.sidebar-title`) are uppercase `0.65rem`,
  `letter-spacing: 1px`, muted grey. Hidden when collapsed.
- Icons inside `.nav-link i` are `0.95rem`, fixed `20px` slot
  (alignment is consistent across the menu).
- Disabled gates: `.sidebar-disabled` (generic),
  `.sidebar-requires-domain` (no domain loaded),
  `.sync-requires-ready` (triplestore empty), `.view-mode-hidden`
  (read-only viewer). Use these classes — do not invent new ones, and
  do not toggle them per page; they're driven by `permissions.js` and
  the `data-domain-saved` body attributes.
- Badges inside a nav-link are auto-wrapped into the `.nav-label`
  span by the collapse logic and hidden when collapsed.

**Don'ts**

- ❌ Hand-coding `<a class="nav-link">` items in the page template —
  the menu is rendered by `partials/layout/_sidebar_nav.html` from
  `menu_config.json`.
- ❌ Calling `addEventListener('click', ...)` on `.nav-link` items to
  intercept switching — use `onBeforeSectionChange` /
  `sidebarSectionChanged`.
- ❌ Toggling `style.display` on `.sidebar-section` directly.
- ❌ Persisting your own per-page sidebar state — there's one
  `localStorage` key for the whole app.
- ❌ Adjusting `--ob-chrome-height` from page code — the breadcrumb
  computes it.

### Breadcrumb Behaviour & Style

The breadcrumb is owned by `global/js/breadcrumb.js` + the
`.ob-breadcrumb` styles in `global/css/components.css`. It is **not**
configured per page — it is fully derived from the URL and the
currently-active sidebar section.

**Behaviour**

- The breadcrumb container `#obBreadcrumb` lives in `base.html` and is
  hidden by default (`d-none`). `breadcrumb.js` auto-runs on
  `DOMContentLoaded`, builds the crumbs and removes `d-none` only when
  there is more than one crumb to show. Pages that never qualify
  (e.g. home, about) keep it hidden — that is intentional, do not
  force it.
- The route hierarchy is fixed in `breadcrumb.js`:
  Registry → Domain → Ontology → Mapping → Digital Twin (plus
  Settings as a flat entry). Adding a new top-level page means
  extending `_ROUTE_MAP` and `_HIERARCHY` there — not patching
  templates.
- The "Domain" crumb label is read from `#currentDomainName` (set by
  the navbar) — do **not** add a separate fetch for the domain name.
- The last crumb is the active sidebar section, updated live on every
  `sidebarSectionChanged` event. Section labels come from the
  sidebar's `.nav-label` text, so renaming a sidebar item
  automatically renames the breadcrumb crumb.
- After rendering, `breadcrumb.js` writes the total chrome height
  (navbar + breadcrumb) into the CSS variable `--ob-chrome-height`,
  which `.sidebar-layout` reads to compute the available viewport
  height. **Don't set this variable from anywhere else.**

**Style**

- Container: `.ob-breadcrumb` — `0.35rem 1rem` padding, light
  background (`var(--bs-light, #f8f9fa)`), bottom border
  (`var(--bs-border-color, #dee2e6)`), font-size `0.8rem`.
- Separator: Bootstrap-icons chevron (`\F285`) at `0.65rem`. Do not
  switch to `/`, `>`, or any other glyph.
- Links: `var(--bs-secondary)`, no underline; underline only on
  `:hover`.
- Active crumb (last item): `var(--bs-body-color)`, weight 500, no
  link.
- Each crumb prefixes its label with a Bootstrap icon (`bi-...`).
  Keep icons consistent with the corresponding sidebar entry.

**Don'ts**

- ❌ Manually mutating `#obBreadcrumbList` from page JS. Use the
  `_ROUTE_MAP` extension or rely on `sidebarSectionChanged`.
- ❌ Adding a per-page breadcrumb (`<nav class="breadcrumb">`) — the
  global one is the only one allowed.
- ❌ Changing the separator, font-size, or padding per page.
- ❌ Forcing the breadcrumb visible on a single-crumb page just to
  display a title — use `.page-header` instead.

### Section / Partial Conventions

- One partial per section. Filename:
  `templates/partials/<area>/_<area>_<feature>.html` (note the leading
  underscore — it marks it as a non-route partial).
- A section partial **never** includes `<link>` or `<script>` tags. All
  CSS/JS is wired in the parent page's `extra_css` / `extra_js` blocks.
- A section partial may include sub-partials but **must not** redefine
  the section wrapper (`<div id="...-section" class="sidebar-section">`)
  — that lives in the page template.

### Section Header & Top-Right Actions

Every section starts with a **`.section-header`** row that pairs a
title block on the left with action buttons on the right. This is the
single allowed pattern for page-level actions — actions never live at
the bottom of a section, never float on top of the content, and never
hide inside a Bootstrap `.card-header`.

**Canonical skeleton**

```html
<div class="section-header d-flex justify-content-between align-items-center mb-4">
    <div>
        <h4 class="mb-1"><i class="bi bi-<icon> me-2"></i>Section Title</h4>
        <p class="text-muted mb-0 small">One-line description of what this section does.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="d-flex gap-2">
        <!-- Utility / icon-only buttons first (refresh, expand/collapse, settings cog) -->
        <div class="btn-group btn-group-sm">
            <button type="button" class="btn btn-outline-secondary" title="Refresh">
                <i class="bi bi-arrow-clockwise"></i>
            </button>
        </div>
        <!-- Secondary CTAs next, primary CTA last (rightmost) -->
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-secondary">
            <i class="bi bi-cloud-download me-1"></i> Load
        </button>
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-sm btn-primary">
            <i class="bi bi-plus-circle me-1"></i> New
        </button>
    </div>
</div>
```

**Rules**

- Action buttons **must** sit in the **top-right** of the section, in
  the right-hand `<div>` of `.section-header`. No exceptions: this is
  the location users learn once and look for everywhere.
- Use `btn-sm` (small). Section headers carry a lot of buttons — full-
  size `.btn` makes them shout.
- Order from left to right: **icon-only utility buttons → secondary
  CTAs → primary CTA**. The rightmost button is the most important
  action of the section.
- Group icon-only utility buttons (refresh, expand all, collapse all,
  settings) inside a `.btn-group.btn-group-sm` so they read as a
  cluster.
- Every icon-only button **must** have a `title=` attribute (and ideally
  `aria-label=`) — it is the only label the user sees.
- Use Bootstrap colour intent (`btn-primary`, `btn-outline-secondary`,
  `btn-success`, `btn-danger`) to communicate hierarchy, even though
  the override in `components.css` neutralises the surface — the
  semantic class still reads correctly to assistive tech and to
  future theme work.
- Buttons with a label start with a Bootstrap icon followed by
  `me-1`, e.g. `<i class="bi bi-plus-circle me-1"></i> Add Entity`.
- Title `<h4>` uses `mb-1`; subtitle `<p>` uses `text-muted mb-0 small`.
  Don't introduce `<h2>`/`<h3>` inside a sidebar section — `.h4` is the
  level for section titles (page-level `<h1>` belongs to
  `.page-header` on standalone pages only).
- The whole row uses `mb-4`. The next sibling is the section's main
  card / content. Don't add a `<hr>` between them — the `mb-4` is the
  separator.

**Anti-patterns**

- ❌ A floating "+" FAB (Material-style) — use the top-right button.
- ❌ Action buttons placed below the data they act on.
- ❌ `<button>` inside `.card-header` of the section's main card —
  wrong location, wrong styling, wrong size.
- ❌ Full-size buttons in a section header.
- ❌ Buttons without an icon, or icon-only buttons without `title=`.
- ❌ Reordering so the primary CTA is on the left.

### Tabs (`.ob-tabs`) — flat-underline style

There is **one** allowed visual treatment for tab navigations
across the app: the flat-underline `ob-tabs` style. It lives in
`global/css/components.css` and was extracted from the Ontology
Designer right-pane tabs (`form-tabs-nav` /
`form-tab-link` in `static/ontology/css/ontology-shared-panels.css`)
and unified with the **Ontology > Cohorts** tab strip — the
canonical reference page for the look.
**Every new tab navigation must use it.** Do not introduce a
boxed/Bootstrap-default look, a pill style, or a per-page custom
tab CSS file.

The class bakes in the full visual contract: white background,
`padding: 0.5rem 1rem 0` (= `px-3 pt-2`), rounded top corners
(`var(--bs-card-border-radius)`), a 1px grey outline on the top /
left / right edges, and a 2px grey baseline at the bottom — the
"underline" — that turns primary-coloured under the active tab.
The strip therefore looks like a card-header (à la Ontology >
Information) out of the box, regardless of whether it sits in a
`.card`, in a `.card-body p-0`, or directly in a section.

When the strip is **inside** a `.card` / `.card-body` / `.card-header`,
the parent card already provides the outer outline. The CSS detects
this via descendant selectors (`.card-body > .nav-tabs.ob-tabs`, …)
and **drops** the strip's own top / left / right border so you never
get a double border. The rounded top corners are **kept** — the
strip is meant to read as a card-header everywhere, including
nested inside another card (cohorts / dq / business-rules /
axioms). When the parent card has `overflow: hidden` (Bootstrap
default), the rounded corners coincide visually with the card's
own outer radius.

When the strip is **followed** by a sibling `.card`,
`.ob-tab-content`, or `.tab-content`, an adjacent-sibling rule
(`.nav-tabs.ob-tabs + .card { border-top: none !important; … }`)
strips the next element's `border-top` and squares its top corners
so the whole tabs + body unit reads as one continuous bordered
shape. **Don't** add `border-top-0 rounded-top-0` on the next
`.card` yourself — it's now redundant (and was the legacy
work-around for the old boxed tabs).

You should never have to re-apply spacing, background or border
utilities on the tab `<ul>` — the strip already looks like the
Ontology > Cohorts header out of the box.

**Canonical skeleton**

```html
<ul class="nav nav-tabs ob-tabs" id="<unique>Tabs" role="tablist">
    <li class="nav-item" role="presentation">
        <button class="nav-link active"
                id="<id>-tab-foo"
                data-bs-toggle="tab"
                data-bs-target="#<id>-pane-foo"
                type="button" role="tab"
                aria-controls="<id>-pane-foo"
                aria-selected="true">
            <i class="bi bi-<icon> me-1"></i>Foo
        </button>
    </li>
    <li class="nav-item" role="presentation">
        <button class="nav-link"
                id="<id>-tab-bar"
                data-bs-toggle="tab"
                data-bs-target="#<id>-pane-bar"
                type="button" role="tab"
                aria-controls="<id>-pane-bar"
                aria-selected="false">
            <i class="bi bi-<icon> me-1"></i>Bar
        </button>
    </li>
</ul>

<div class="tab-content" id="<id>TabContent">
    <div class="tab-pane fade show active" id="<id>-pane-foo"
         role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="<id>-tab-foo">
        ...
    </div>
    <div class="tab-pane fade" id="<id>-pane-bar"
         role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="<id>-tab-bar">
        ...
    </div>
</div>
```

**Rules**

- The tab `<ul>` **must** carry both `nav nav-tabs` (for Bootstrap
  behaviour) **and** `ob-tabs` (for the visual treatment). The
  `ob-tabs` class is a drop-in addition; Bootstrap's
  `data-bs-toggle="tab"` keeps working unchanged.
- Every tab button starts with a Bootstrap icon
  (`<i class="bi bi-<icon> me-1"></i>`) followed by the label.
  Never an icon-less tab.
- The active state is rendered as a 2px primary-coloured
  underline. Active colour and weight are owned by `ob-tabs`
  in `components.css` — **don't override** `.nav-link.active`
  in a per-area file.
- **Font-size is intentionally inherited.** This is so each page
  keeps its existing sizing — don't set `font-size` on the
  `ob-tabs` selector itself. If a section needs smaller tabs
  (e.g. Data Quality, Business Rules, Inference, Axioms), apply
  Bootstrap's `.small` to the `<ul>`. If a section needs a
  one-off size (e.g. Cohort uses `0.9rem`), put **only** that
  font-size override in the area's CSS file, scoped to the
  area-specific class — never re-declare colour, padding,
  border-bottom, or hover/active styles.
- The only Bootstrap utilities that should sit alongside
  `ob-tabs` are layout / sizing helpers (`nav-fill`,
  `flex-shrink-0`, `mb-0`) and the size hint `.small`. The
  catalogued combinations in the codebase are:
  - `nav nav-tabs ob-tabs mb-0` — Domain / Settings.
  - `nav nav-tabs ob-tabs` — Import / Wizard / Ontology Cohorts.
  - `nav nav-tabs ob-tabs nav-fill` — Ontology DQ / Business
    Rules / Axioms.
  - `nav nav-tabs ob-tabs nav-fill flex-shrink-0` —
    DT-DataQuality / DT-Inference (the `flex-shrink-0` keeps the
    tab strip a fixed-size header inside their flex card body).
  - The `.nav-link` font-size is now baked into `ob-tabs`
    (`0.9rem`), so the legacy `.small` modifier is no longer
    needed and has been removed from the dq / business-rules /
    axioms / dt pages. Don't add it back.
- Do **not** re-apply spacing utilities on the tab `<ul>`. The
  padding (`px-3 pt-2` equivalent) and white background are
  already baked in. Adding `px-3 pt-3` / `pt-2` / `pt-3` /
  `bg-white` on top double-pads the strip and breaks alignment
  between sibling pages.
- Do **not** add `style="gap: 2px;"` (or any inline `style`)
  on the tab `<ul>` — the gap of 0 is set by `ob-tabs` and is
  what makes the underline read as one continuous baseline.
- The tab content can sit inside a Bootstrap `.card` or stand
  alone. The adjacent-sibling rule
  (`.nav-tabs.ob-tabs + .card { border-top: none !important; … }`)
  fuses the strip and the next `.card` / `.ob-tab-content` /
  `.tab-content` into one bordered shape — **don't** add
  `border-top-0 rounded-top-0` yourself.
- **Full-height pattern (preferred for tabbed pages).** Tabs +
  body should fill the page from below the section header to the
  bottom of the viewport, exactly like the single card on
  Ontology > Information. Two ways to achieve this:
  1. Place the `<ul ob-tabs>` and the body card as **direct
     children of `.content-section`**. The existing
     `sidebar-layout.css` rule
     `.sidebar-section > .content-section > .card { flex: 1 }`
     stretches the body card to fill (Domain / Settings /
     Ontology Import / DT Inference work this way).
  2. Wrap the strip and the body in a `<div class="ob-tabs-wrap">`
     when you need the same fill behaviour deeper in the markup
     (e.g. inside another flex column). `ob-tabs-wrap` is a
     flex-column container that pins the strip via
     `flex-shrink: 0` and gives `flex: 1 + overflow-y: auto` to
     its child `.tab-content` / `.ob-tab-content` / `.card`.
     When `ob-tabs-wrap` is itself a direct child of
     `.content-section`, it grows to fill the section.
- The legacy boxed pane `.ob-tab-content` is preserved for
  pages that still need a bordered content area, but new tabs
  should default to plain `.tab-content` (no boxed wrapper).
  Reach for `.ob-tab-content` only when the tab content
  genuinely needs a bordered/padded surface independent of any
  parent `.card`.

**Anti-patterns**

- ❌ Bare `<ul class="nav nav-tabs">` without `ob-tabs` — that
  triggers the legacy boxed look.
- ❌ Pill tabs (`nav-pills`) anywhere in the app.
- ❌ Per-area redeclaration of `.nav-link` colour, padding,
  border-bottom, or `.nav-link.active` styling. The whole point
  of `ob-tabs` is one shared treatment.
- ❌ Re-applying `px-3 pt-2` / `px-3 pt-3` / `bg-white` on the
  tab `<ul>` — those are baked into `ob-tabs`. Stacking them
  double-pads the strip.
- ❌ Adding Bootstrap's `.small` (or any `font-size` override) on
  the tab `<ul>` or `.nav-link`. The unified `0.9rem` size is
  baked into `ob-tabs` so every tab head reads at the same size
  across the app.
- ❌ Re-applying `border-top-0 rounded-top-0` on the `.card`
  that follows `<ul ob-tabs>` — the adjacent-sibling rule
  already handles it. Leaving the utility there is harmless but
  noisy.
- ❌ A short, free-floating tabs-card that doesn't fill the page
  height. Use the *Full-height pattern* above (direct children of
  `.content-section`, or `.ob-tabs-wrap`) so the tabs reach the
  bottom of the viewport like the Ontology > Information card.
- ❌ Inline `style="gap:…"` or `style="font-size:…"` on the tab
  `<ul>` — use `.small` or an area class.
- ❌ Hand-rolled tab JS (clicks toggling `display: none`).
  Always use Bootstrap's `data-bs-toggle="tab"` so keyboard
  navigation, ARIA and `shown.bs.tab` events are free.
- ❌ Tabs without icons or without `aria-selected` /
  `aria-controls`.
- ❌ Adding tab styles to `main.css`'s `.nav-tabs` block —
  that's the legacy fallback. New work goes through
  `.ob-tabs` in `components.css`.

### Component Naming

| Prefix | Owner | Use |
|--------|-------|-----|
| `ob-*` | OntoBricks shared components | Cross-page reusable widgets (`ob-kpi-tile`, `ob-breadcrumb`, `ob-shortcut-card`, `ob-loading-spinner`, `ob-tabs`, `ob-tab-content`) |
| `ovz-*` | OntoViz canvas | Entities, relationships, toolbar, context menu inside the OntoViz library |
| Bootstrap classes | Bootstrap 5.3.2 | Base utilities and layout primitives |
| Area-specific | Per-area CSS files | Local concerns; prefer to first reuse an `ob-*` component |

When introducing a new shared component:

1. Pick the `ob-*` prefix.
2. Place styles in `global/css/components.css` (or a new file under
   `global/css/` if the component is large enough to deserve its own file
   and load it in `base.html`).
3. Document the component contract in a short comment block at the top of
   its CSS section (selector skeleton + variants), in the style of
   `.ob-kpi-tile` in `components.css`.

### Reusable Components Catalog

These already exist; reuse before reinventing.

- **KPI tile** — `.ob-kpi-tile` with optional state variants
  (`.tile-success`, `.tile-danger`, `.tile-warning`, `.tile-muted`) and
  bottom-accent variants (`.tile-accent-*`). Sub-elements:
  `.ob-kpi-tile-icon`, `.ob-kpi-tile-value`, `.ob-kpi-tile-label`.
- **Loading spinner** — one brand spinner app-wide. Inline: plain Bootstrap
  `.spinner-border` (auto-repainted to the brand spinner by `main.css`).
  Large/centered: `.ob-loading-spinner` with `.ob-spinner-svg` and optional
  `.ob-spinner-label` (SVG markup is in `base.html` — do not redraw the
  rings/diamond — include the partial or copy verbatim). See
  *Loading Spinners* for the full contract.
- **Page-level loading overlay** — `.domain-loading-overlay` already wired
  in `base.html` as `#domainLoadingOverlay`. Toggle via `.d-none`.
- **Breadcrumb** — `.ob-breadcrumb` driven by `breadcrumb.js`; do not
  build a parallel breadcrumb.
- **Tabs** — `.nav.nav-tabs.ob-tabs` (flat-underline). One shared
  visual treatment defined in `components.css`; see
  *Tabs (`.ob-tabs`) — flat-underline style* above for the canonical
  skeleton, allowed combinations and anti-patterns. The legacy
  `.ob-tab-content` is kept only for the rare case where a bordered
  pane is genuinely needed.
- **Cards** — Bootstrap `.card` / `.card-header`; styling already neutered
  to project tokens.
- **Forms** — Bootstrap `.form-control` / `.form-select` / `.form-label`;
  focus ring is already themed.
- **Alerts** — Bootstrap `.alert` with `.alert-success` / `.alert-danger`
  using project status background tokens.
- **Wizard overlay** — `.wizard-form-overlay` for absolute-positioned
  blocking spinners over a form during async tasks.
- **Keyboard shortcut overlay** — `.ob-shortcut-overlay` + `.ob-shortcut-card`.

### Loading Spinners

There is **one** loading-spinner look across the whole app: the **OntoBricks
brand spinner** (the rotating node-ring + diamond). Never introduce a second
spinner style.

**How it works.** A global override in `global/css/main.css` repaints every
Bootstrap `.spinner-border` / `.spinner-grow` into the brand spinner (it drops
the border + Bootstrap rotation and paints
`background: url(/static/global/img/loading-spinner.svg)`; the SVG self-animates
via SMIL). So **the standard way to show an inline spinner is plain Bootstrap
markup** — it is automatically branded, at every call site, present and future:

```html
<div class="spinner-border" role="status" aria-hidden="true"></div>
<!-- small variant -->
<div class="spinner-border spinner-border-sm" role="status" aria-hidden="true"></div>
```

Size is controlled by Bootstrap's own `width/height` (and the `-sm` modifier) —
do not set a custom size that fights the override.

**Pick the right tool:**

| Need | Use |
|------|-----|
| Inline spinner in a button, cell, or while a section loads | Bootstrap `.spinner-border` (auto-branded). Add a label in a sibling `<span>` if needed. |
| Large, centered spinner with a caption (panel/empty-state) | `.ob-loading-spinner` + `.ob-spinner-svg` + optional `.ob-spinner-label`. SVG markup lives in `base.html` — include the partial or copy it **verbatim**; never redraw the rings/diamond. |
| Full-page domain load | The existing `#domainLoadingOverlay` / `.domain-loading-overlay` in `base.html` (toggle `.d-none`). |

`.spin-animation` (a rotating **status** icon for running tasks) is **not** a
loading spinner — leave it as is.

**Don'ts**

- ❌ A new spinner style — custom `@keyframes` ring, a third-party/SVG spinner
  library, an emoji/`bi-hourglass` "loading" glyph, or an `<img>` of a
  different spinner. Use the Bootstrap spinner (auto-branded) or
  `.ob-loading-spinner`.
- ❌ Overriding `.spinner-border` / `.spinner-grow` to re-add a border, change
  the animation, or repaint the background — that defeats the single brand
  spinner. The override lives once in `main.css`.
- ❌ Redrawing the brand spinner SVG (`loading-spinner.svg` / the
  `.ob-spinner-svg` rings + diamond) in page code.

### Popups, Modals, Confirmations & Notifications

**Two non-negotiable rules:**

1. **Native browser popups are forbidden.** Never call `alert()`,
   `confirm()`, or `prompt()` from any frontend code. They bypass our
   design system, block the main thread, look like a 2003 Windows error,
   and cannot be tested from JS.
2. **All user-facing messages route through the navbar Notification
   Center.** There is one message bus for the whole app — the bell
   dropdown in the top-right of the navbar (`#notifCenterDropdown`),
   backed by the `NotificationCenter` singleton in
   `global/js/utils.js`. Every success / error / warning / info that a
   user should see goes through `showNotification(...)`. No
   per-page toasts. No inline `<div class="alert">` blocks bolted on as
   a status line. No console-only errors for things the user needs to
   know.

#### Single message bus — the navbar Notification Center

The Notification Center is provided by `base.html` and runs on every
page:

- Bell toggle: `#notifCenterToggle` (icon `bi-bell`).
- Dropdown: `#notifCenterDropdown` with list `#notifCenterList`.
- Unread badge: `#notifCenterBadge` (auto-managed; shows `99+` past 99).
- Buffer: in-memory ring buffer capped by
  `<html data-max-notifications>` (default `10`).
- Each entry shows icon + message + relative time
  (`just now`, `5s ago`, `12m ago`, `3h ago`, then absolute date).
- Opening the dropdown marks all entries read; the user can clear all
  via the trash button in the dropdown header.

**The only API you should call is `showNotification(message, type,
duration?)`.** It pushes to the centre **and** flashes a transient
toast for `success` / `warning` / `error` so urgent messages are
immediately visible without forcing the user to open the bell.

#### What goes through the Notification Center

| Source of the message | Route via |
|------------------------|-----------|
| API call result (success / failure) | `showNotification(...)` in the page's `.then` / `.catch` |
| Form validation error before submit | `showNotification(msg, 'warning')` (then keep the form open) |
| Background task progress / completion | Already wired via the Task Tracker (`task-tracker.js`) — listen, don't reinvent |
| Confirmation of a destructive action | `await showDeleteConfirm(name, type)` — its outcome should still produce a `showNotification` when done |
| Question requiring user choice | `await showConfirmDialog({...})` |
| Free-text input | A purpose-built Bootstrap modal with a `<form>` — never `prompt()` |
| Long-form details (preview, help) | A Bootstrap modal (`DocumentPreview.open(...)` or area-specific) |

#### What to use instead

| You want to… | Use | Where it's defined |
|--------------|-----|---------------------|
| Tell the user something happened (info / success / warning / error) | `showNotification(message, type, duration?)` | `global/js/utils.js` |
| Ask Yes/No | `await showConfirmDialog({ title, message, confirmText, cancelText, confirmClass, icon })` | `global/js/utils.js` |
| Confirm a delete | `await showDeleteConfirm(itemName, itemType?)` (red themed) | `global/js/utils.js` |
| Preview a file | `DocumentPreview.open(filename)` | `global/js/utils.js` |
| Get a string from the user | A purpose-built Bootstrap modal with a `<form>` and an explicit Cancel/Save footer — never `prompt()`. |
| Modal with custom content | A Bootstrap 5 modal in a Jinja partial, opened via `bootstrap.Modal.getOrCreateInstance(modalEl).show()` |

`showNotification` already pushes the message into the navbar
Notification Center bell **and** displays a transient toast for
`error` / `warning` / `success`. Use it as the single entry point for
all user-facing feedback. Toast styling lives in `pages.css`
(`.error-toast-popup`, `.warning-toast-popup`, `.success-toast-popup`,
`#errorToastContainer`) — do not reimplement.

#### Type → toast policy

| `type` | Notification Center | Floating toast | Default duration |
|--------|---------------------|----------------|------------------|
| `info` | yes | no | n/a |
| `success` | yes | yes | 3000 ms |
| `warning` | yes | yes | 4000 ms |
| `error` | yes | yes | 6000 ms |

Messages ending in `...` are treated as transient progress messages and
are deliberately **not** added to the Notification Center — only shown
as toasts. Use this for "Saving...", "Loading...", etc.

#### Bootstrap modal pattern (for purpose-built dialogs)

Every modal that's not produced by a helper above must:

1. Live in a partial under `templates/partials/<area>/_<area>_<feature>_modal.html`
   (or a shared one under `templates/partials/layout/` if cross-area),
   and be `{% include %}`'d by the page template.
2. Use the standard Bootstrap structure:
   ```html
   <div class="modal fade" id="<purpose>Modal" tabindex="-1">
       <div class="modal-dialog modal-dialog-centered">
           <div class="modal-content">
               <div class="modal-header">
                   <h5 class="modal-title">
                       <i class="bi bi-<icon> me-2"></i>Title
                   </h5>
                   <button type="button" class="btn-close" data-bs-dismiss="modal"></button>
               </div>
               <div class="modal-body">...</div>
               <div class="modal-footer">
                   <button type="button" class="btn btn-secondary" data-bs-dismiss="modal">Cancel</button>
                   <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" id="<purpose>SaveBtn">Save</button>
               </div>
           </div>
       </div>
   </div>
   ```
3. Be opened from JS via:
   ```js
   const modalEl = document.getElementById('<purpose>Modal');
   const modal = bootstrap.Modal.getOrCreateInstance(modalEl);
   modal.show();
   ```
   Use `getOrCreateInstance` (idempotent), never `new bootstrap.Modal(...)`
   each time.
4. Always include the `data-bs-dismiss="modal"` button-close pattern so
   Esc / backdrop click / Cancel all behave consistently.
5. Never use inline `style="..."` on the modal — if a custom width is
   needed, use Bootstrap's `modal-lg` / `modal-xl` modifier or add a
   class in the matching CSS file.

#### Reusing existing modals before building a new one

Before adding a new modal, check whether one of these can be reused:

- `partials/layout/uc_file_browser_modal.html` — Unity Catalog file
  picker (`window.openUCFileBrowser(...)`).
- `partials/layout/help_modal.html` — Help Center.
- `DocumentPreview.open(filename)` — generic document viewer
  (PDF / image / text).
- `showConfirmDialog(...)` / `showDeleteConfirm(...)` — yes/no prompts.

If the use case fits one of these (even loosely), extend it rather than
duplicating modal scaffolding.

### Static Asset Folder Layout

```
src/front/static/
├── global/                <- Cross-page assets
│   ├── css/               <- main.css, components.css, pages.css,
│   │                         sidebar-layout.css, permissions.css, …
│   ├── js/                <- navbar.js, sidebar-nav.js, breadcrumb.js,
│   │                         permissions.js, utils.js, task-tracker.js, …
│   ├── img/               <- logos, favicons, spinners (SVG)
│   └── ontoviz/           <- The OntoViz library (CSS + JS together)
│       ├── css/
│       └── ontoviz.js
├── <area>/                <- One folder per area
│   ├── css/               <- <area>-<feature>.css (e.g. query-cohorts.css)
│   └── js/                <- <area>-<feature>.js
└── config/
```

**Area folders mirror partial folders.** A new file at
`templates/partials/<area>/_<feature>.html` should pair with assets at
`static/<area>/{css,js}/<area>-<feature>.{css,js}`.

### Asset Wiring (in `base.html` / page templates)

- Always cache-bust with `?v={{ asset_version }}`. The bare `?v=2` literal
  is reserved for the favicon.
- Load order in `base.html` is fixed; do not reorder:
  1. Bootstrap CSS (CDN)
  2. Bootstrap Icons (CDN)
  3. `main.css` → `components.css` → `pages.css` → `sidebar-layout.css`
     → `emoji-picker.css` → `help-modal.css`
  4. `permissions.css` **must load LAST** so its `!important` role/version
     gates win over per-component rules.
- `permissions.js` **must be the first deferred script** so
  `window.OB.permissions` is defined before navbar/version-check read it.
- Per-page CSS/JS goes in `{% block extra_css %}` / `{% block extra_js %}`,
  also cache-busted.

### Read-Only & Role Gating

- Role/version gating is centralised in `global/css/permissions.css` and
  driven by body classes set by `permissions.js`:
  `body.read-only-version`, `body.role-viewer`.
- Inputs and action affordances are hidden / disabled via `body:is(...)`
  selectors with `!important`. Do not duplicate this logic per page.
- Server side, `data-app-role`, `data-domain-role` and `data-app-mode` are
  set on `<body>` in `base.html` — read them from JS rather than calling
  the API again.

### Accessibility Baseline

- Every interactive icon-only control has a `title=` (and ideally
  `aria-label=`). See navbar bell / hourglass / help icons.
- Decorative SVGs (chevrons, spinner glyphs) have `aria-hidden="true"`.
- Modals use Bootstrap's modal markup so focus trapping and ESC are free.
- Maintain Bootstrap's contrast: do not lighten text below
  `--db-text-muted` for body copy.

### What NOT to Do

- ❌ `alert()`, `confirm()`, `prompt()` — use `showNotification`,
  `showConfirmDialog`, `showDeleteConfirm`, or a Bootstrap modal.
- ❌ A per-page toast container, alert banner, or status `<div>` for
  user feedback. Use the navbar Notification Center.
- ❌ `console.error(...)` as the only signal that something failed —
  mirror it with a `showNotification(msg, 'error')`.
- ❌ `new bootstrap.Modal(el)` on each open — use
  `bootstrap.Modal.getOrCreateInstance(el)`.
- ❌ Per-page reimplementation of the navbar, breadcrumb, KPI tile,
  loading spinner, modal scaffolding, sidebar layout, notification
  centre, task tracker, help centre, or UC file browser.
- ❌ A page template that does not `{% extends "base.html" %}`.
- ❌ Top-level page markup that is neither `.sidebar-layout` nor a
  page-header + standalone block — no third pattern.
- ❌ Action buttons placed anywhere other than the top-right of the
  section's `.section-header`. No floating FABs, no bottom action
  bars, no buttons inside `.card-header`.
- ❌ Hand-coded sidebar `<a class="nav-link">` items — use
  `_sidebar_nav.html` + `menu_config.json`.
- ❌ `addEventListener('click', ...)` on sidebar nav links — use the
  `sidebarSectionChanged` event or `onBeforeSectionChange` hook.
- ❌ Setting `style.display` on `.sidebar-section` directly — toggle
  the `.active` class via `SidebarNav.switchTo(...)`.
- ❌ Writing `--ob-chrome-height` from page code — that's the
  breadcrumb's responsibility.
- ❌ A custom per-page breadcrumb. Extend `_ROUTE_MAP` in
  `breadcrumb.js` instead.
- ❌ Bare `<ul class="nav nav-tabs">` (no `ob-tabs`), pill tabs,
  or per-area redeclaration of `.nav-link` / `.nav-link.active`
  styles. All tab nav uses the shared `ob-tabs` flat-underline
  treatment from `components.css` (see *Tabs (`.ob-tabs`) —
  flat-underline style*).
- ❌ A second spinner style. Use the single brand spinner — inline via
  Bootstrap `.spinner-border` (auto-branded) or `.ob-loading-spinner` for
  large/centered cases. No custom keyframes, spinner libraries, emoji/
  `bi-hourglass` "loading" glyphs, or `.spinner-border` overrides (see
  *Loading Spinners*).
- ❌ Inline `<style>` or `style="…"` in templates. Move to
  `static/<area>/css/`.
- ❌ Inline `<script>` blocks beyond a single tiny bootstrap call. Move
  to `static/<area>/js/`.
- ❌ Hard-coded hex/rgb colours when a token exists.
- ❌ Importing webfonts, FontAwesome, Material Icons, or any
  non-Bootstrap icon font.
- ❌ Coloured Bootstrap buttons expecting their default look.
- ❌ Mixing `--db-*` and `--ovz-*` tokens in the same selector.
- ❌ Loading `permissions.css` anywhere other than last, or
  `permissions.js` anywhere other than first-defer.
- ❌ Sidebar nav items hand-coded in templates instead of via
  `menu_config.json` + `_sidebar_nav.html`.
- ❌ Inline modal markup created from JS string templates for ad-hoc
  dialogs — put the markup in a partial and `{% include %}` it.
